$\require{AMScd}$ There is a retraction of $D^n\times I\twoheadrightarrow (D^n×\{0\})\cup (S^{n-1}×I)$ defined via $$r(x,t)=\begin{cases}
\left(\frac{2x}{2-t},\ 0\right)             &\text{, if }t\le2(1-||x||) \\
\left(\frac x{||x||},2-\frac{2-t}{||x||}\right)&\text{, if }t\ge2(1-||x||)
\end{cases}$$ It is easy to prove that this map is well-defined and continuous and a retraction. Then $$d:D^n×I×I\to D^n×I\\ d(x,t,s)=sr(x,t)+(1-s)(x,t)$$ is a homotopy between the identity and $r$ , so $r$ is a deformation retraction.
But then $(D^n×I)\cup_H X$ deformation retracts onto $(\ (D^n×\{0\})\cup (S^{n-1}×I)\ )\cup_H X=(D^n×\{0\})\cup_f X$ Note that a pushout square ( $A,X$ , and $B$ are arbitrary spaces) \begin{CD}
A @>f>> B\\@ViVV @VV\tilde iV\\ X @>>\tilde f> X\cup_f B
\end{CD} gives rise to a pushout square \begin{CD}
A\times I @>f>> B \times I\\@ViVV @VV\tilde iV\\ X\times I @>>\tilde f> (X\cup_f B)\times I
\end{CD} because the quotient map $q:X\sqcup B\to X\cup_f B$ induces a quotient map $q\times 1:X\times I\sqcup B\times I\to(X\cup_f B)\times I$ . This means that a pair of homotopies $F_t:X→Y$ , $G_t:B→Y$ , such that $F_ti=G_t f$ for all $t\in I$ , induces a homotopy $H_t:X∪_f B→Y$ That's the reason why a deformation retraction on $D^n×I$ induces a deformation retraction on the pushout $(D^n×I)\cup_F X$ There is more general result: If $(X,A)$ is cofibered, then $X×I$ deformation retracts to $(X×\{0\})\cup (A×I)$ , so if $X$ is glued via two homotopic maps $f$ and $g$ to a space $B$ , then $X\cup_f B$ and $X\cup_g B$ are homotopy equivalent.
